            <div class="treatment-description">
              <h4>How It Works</h4>
              <p>
                Manual removal uses specialized instruments such as curettes, forceps, and probes to carefully extract ear wax. This method requires significant skill and experience, and is typically reserved for specific situations where other methods may not be suitable.
              </p>

              <h4>When It's Used</h4>
              <ul class="usage-scenarios">
                <li>Very hard, impacted wax that won't respond to other methods</li>
                <li>Foreign objects mixed with wax</li>
                <li>Unusual ear canal anatomy</li>
                <li>When microsuction or irrigation aren't suitable</li>
                <li>Specific patient preferences or medical requirements</li>
              </ul>

              <h4>Instruments Used</h4>
              <div class="instruments-list">
                <div class="instrument">
                  <strong>Otoscope:</strong> Illuminated magnification for visualization
                </div>
                <div class="instrument">
                  <strong>Curettes:</strong> Small spoon-shaped tools for scooping wax
                </div>
                <div class="instrument">
                  <strong>Forceps:</strong> Precision gripping tools for larger pieces
                </div>
                <div class="instrument">
                  <strong>Probes:</strong> Fine instruments for breaking up hard wax
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="treatment-benefits">
